## Manual posterior predictive summary (explicit matrix operations & sampling; supersedes legacy link()/sim() convenience calls)
## to avoid unsupported arguments or version-specific behavior.

post <- extract.samples(m5.3)             # posterior draws
n_draws <- length(post$a)

# Construct matrix of mu samples: rows = draws, cols = cases
mu_samples <- vapply(seq_len(nrow(d)), function(i) {
  post$a + post$bM * d$M[i] + post$bA * d$A[i]
}, numeric(n_draws))

mu_mean <- apply(mu_samples, 2, mean)
mu_PI   <- apply(mu_samples, 2, PI, prob = 0.89)

# Posterior predictive simulations: one simulated observation per draw per case
D_sim <- vapply(seq_len(nrow(d)), function(i) {
  rnorm(n_draws, mu_samples[, i], post$sigma)
}, numeric(n_draws))
D_PI <- apply(D_sim, 2, PI, prob = 0.89)

plot( mu_mean ~ d$D, col = rangi2, ylim = range(mu_PI), 
      xlab = "observed divorce rate", 
      ylab = "predicted divorce rate")

abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2)
for (i  in 1 : nrow(d)) lines( rep(d$D[i], 2), mu_PI[, i], col = rangi2)

Posterior predictive plot for the divorce model, m5.3. The horizontal axis is the observed divorce rate in each state. The vertical axis is the models posterior predicted divorce rate, given each states median age at marriage and marriage rate. The blue line segments are 89% compatibility intervals. The diagonal line shows where posterior predictions exactly match the sample.

sim() posterior samples manualcounterfactual A posterior M M D D sim() 

## Manual counterfactual simulation (explicit posterior sampling; replaces historical sim(m5.3_A, ... ) helper)
## Draw posterior samples, generate M then D for each A in A_seq.

sim_dat <- data.frame(A = A_seq)
post_cf <- extract.samples(m5.3_A)
n_draws <- length(post_cf$a)

# For each A value, compute M mean and simulate M, then compute D mean and simulate D.
sim_list_D <- vector("list", length(A_seq))
for(j in seq_along(A_seq)) {
  A_val <- A_seq[j]
  mu_M_j <- post_cf$aM + post_cf$bAM * A_val
  M_sim_j <- rnorm(n_draws, mu_M_j, post_cf$sigma_M)
  mu_D_j <- post_cf$a + post_cf$bM * M_sim_j + post_cf$bA * A_val
  D_sim_j <- rnorm(n_draws, mu_D_j, post_cf$sigma)
  sim_list_D[[j]] <- D_sim_j
}

# Combine into matrix: rows = draws, cols = A values
D_cf_mat <- do.call(cbind, sim_list_D)

# Summary intervals for D
D_cf_mean <- apply(D_cf_mat, 2, mean)
D_cf_PI   <- apply(D_cf_mat, 2, PI, prob = 0.89)

# Store for later plotting
cf_total <- list(A = A_seq, mean = D_cf_mean, PI = D_cf_PI)

# Effect of raising median age at marriage from 20 to 30 (standardized scale)
age_mean <- 26.1
age_sd   <- 1.24
A_vals_std <- (c(20,30) - age_mean) / age_sd
if(!exists("post_cf")) post_cf <- extract.samples(m5.3_A)
n_draws <- length(post_cf$a)
# Simulate sequentially: A -> M then M,A -> D for both A values
simulate_D_for_A <- function(A_std){
  mu_M <- post_cf$aM + post_cf$bAM * A_std
  M_sim <- rnorm(n_draws, mu_M, post_cf$sigma_M)
  mu_D <- post_cf$a + post_cf$bM * M_sim + post_cf$bA * A_std
  rnorm(n_draws, mu_D, post_cf$sigma)
}
D_A20 <- simulate_D_for_A(A_vals_std[1])
D_A30 <- simulate_D_for_A(A_vals_std[2])

Manipulating M means we break the arrow from A to M.

@ref(fig:introBayes08-fig14) M A M 

# Manual counterfactual simulation: manipulate M while fixing A = 0
sim_dat <- data.frame( M = seq(from = -2 , to = 2, length.out = 30), A = 0)
post_cf <- if(!exists("post_cf")) extract.samples(m5.3_A) else post_cf
n_draws <- length(post_cf$a)
# For each manipulated M value, simulate D from posterior
D_M_mat <- sapply(sim_dat$M, function(M_val){
  mu_D <- post_cf$a + post_cf$bM * M_val + post_cf$bA * 0
  rnorm(n_draws, mu_D, post_cf$sigma)
})
D_M_mean <- colMeans(D_M_mat)
D_M_PI   <- apply(D_M_mat, 2, PI, prob = 0.89)
plot(sim_dat$M, D_M_mean, ylim = c(-2, 2), type = "l",
  xlab = "manipulated M", ylab = "counterfactual D")
shade(D_M_PI, sim_dat$M)
mtext("Total counterfactual effect of M on D")

The counterfactual effect of manipulating marriage rate M on divorce rate D. Since M -> D was estimated to be very small, there is no strong trend here. By manipulating M, we break the influence of A on M, and this removes the association between M and D.
